            <h1 class="section-title">Mission & Motive</h1>

            <p class="section-text">
                We are driven by a simple, undeniable truth: the ocean is dying in plain sight, and we refuse to stand
                by and watch. Our motive is born from the devastating reality of the numbers. In the last 50 years
                alone, the global population of oceanic sharks and rays has plummeted by a catastrophic 71%, a direct
                result of an 18-fold increase in fishing pressure since 1970 (Pacoureau et al., 2021). Annually, an
                estimated 80 million sharks are killed to supply the voracious international fin trade, a number that
                remains tragically unchecked (Cardeñosa et al., 2023).
            </p>

            <p class="section-text">
                This isn't just a tragedy; it's a systemic failure. We are allowing the guardians of our ocean to be
                annihilated because our methods of protection are outdated, blind, and fundamentally broken.
            </p>

            <p class="section-text">
                Our mission is to close this critical gap between ignorance and action. We build the tools to make the
                invisible, visible.
            </p>

            <p class="section-text">
                We achieve this by fusing NASA's orbital perspective with our pioneering smart-tag technology. Project
                Sentinel is not just a platform; it is our answer to the crisis. It is the instrument that provides the
                real-time, predictive data needed to empower scientists, guide policy, and transform a failing, reactive
                conservation effort into a proactive, data-driven science. Our motive is to stop the decline. Our
                mission is to provide the light needed to find the way.
            </p>

